	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64247750"><p><div class="quote"><p>BS.
I would argue they would force people to pay more and get less if they actually introduced ECC support in those CPUs.
Most people in the target group wouldn't need it, therefore they would pay more for a feature that's useless to them. And if some of the others wanted it, they would have had to also get ECC RAM, at which point they would be better off getting a Pro CPU.</p></div><p>I would argue that everyone needs ECC RAM.  Sure, a random bit flip causing a crash or hard drive corruption every so often might not be the end of the world, but it still sucks.  ECC should be the default, not the exception.  The tiny extra cost in the overall price of computers caused by eliminating non-ECC RAM across the board would be well worth it in terms of overall stability.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64247750">
