<div id="comment_status_64248190" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64248190" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64248190" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64248190" name="comment_link_64248190" href="//slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23230076&amp;cid=64248190" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64248190)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64248190" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64248190); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~dgatwood">dgatwood</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~dgatwood">( 11270 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64248190"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64248190"><p><div class="quote"><p>I would argue that everyone shouldn't need to pay extra for suffering one extra crash per maybe thousand people per lifetime of their PCs.</p></div><p>The probability of one-bit errors is proportional to the amount of RAM.  When computers had 64k of RAM, that might have been a realistic number.  With the average computer having five orders of magnitude more RAM, the probability is five orders of magnitude greater.</p><p>Some studies have shown as much as 1 bit error per gigabyte of RAM per 1.8 hours.  That means over a person's lifetime, a computer with 16 GB of RAM, the average person would experience over 6 *million* one-bit errors.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64248190">

</div>
</div>

