		<div id="comment_body_64248254"><p>There is a significant amount of errors introduced on the data lines between CPU and memory module. For starters the signal voltage is quite low on DDR5 (1.1V) and impedance is around 50 Ohms. It doesn't take much external noise to occasionally insert bit errors in a transmissoin. And that's assuming your DDR5's on-die termination is working correctly, without ODT I doubt DDR5 would even be viable as a memory standard. Regardless of error correction.</p><p>Moving forward, I think that so-called "consumer grade mem<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
